Input is `abc\n`. What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int n = 99;
    if (std::cin >> n) {
        std::cout << "ok " << n << "\n";
    } else {
        std::cout << "fail " << n << "\n";
    }
}
```

Input is `5 7 3\n` (followed by EOF). What does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int x, sum = 0;
    while (std::cin >> x) sum += x;
    std::cout << sum << "\n";
}
```

This program is supposed to read integers until EOF and print their sum, but it loops forever when given non-integer input. What is the bug?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int x, sum = 0;
    while (!std::cin.eof()) {
        std::cin >> x;
        sum += x;
    }
    std::cout << sum << "\n";
}
```
